<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911119-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>911119-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Alliant Computer Systems Corp.:   Supercomputer Is Introduced   With Up to 800 Processors</HL><DATE>11/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   ALNTC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Alliant Computer Systems Corp., Littleton, Mass., said itintroduced a supercomputer that can be equipped with as manyas 800 internal processors working together.   Alliant's supercomputer uses a technology called massivelyparallel processing, which speeds up computing tasks by usingmany internal &quot;brains,&quot; or processors, that break problemsinto pieces that are processed simultaneously.</LP><TEXT>   The Alliant machine will use i860 RISC processors made byIntel Corp. Alliant said it believes that its machine will beeasier to program than other parallel processingsupercomputers on the market. The price of Alliant'ssupercomputer will range from $2.5 million for a system with100 processors to $16 million for an 800-processor system.</TEXT></DOC>